The paper discusses a data visualization technique, specifically t-SNE, which is commonly used in machine learning and computer vision. Therefore, the most likely sub-category is cs.LG (Machine Learning). The paper also discusses the use of t-SNE on real-life data sets such as MNIST and single-cell RNA-sequencing data, which are commonly used in computer vision and bioinformatics, respectively. This suggests that cs.CV (Computer Vision) and cs.SI (Social and Information Networks) are also likely sub-categories. Additionally, the paper mentions the use of domain knowledge to confirm the meaningfulness of the revealed clusters, which suggests that cs.AI (Artificial Intelligence) may also be a relevant sub-category. Finally, the paper discusses the use of t-SNE on text data from the HathiTrust library, which suggests that cs.CL (Computation and Language) may also be a relevant sub-category.
